            <biogHist>
                <p>Mary Carmichael, daughter of Hugh Carmichael, tailor, and Margaret Carmichael née
                    MacNiven, was born in the parish of Appin. Evidently she had an illegitimate
                    child: this may or may not have been the girl recorded as her eight-year-old
                    niece Bell Carmichael from Hamilton who was living with her in Achnacreebeag,
                    Ardchattan Parish, in 1851 when she is first traceable on the census. Although
                    Mary was then recorded as a pauper (labourer), by 1861 she was working as a
                    dairymaid, living by herself in the same house. Ten years later she is recorded
                    as a domestic servant in the household of Hugh MacColl, unmarried farmer at
                    Dalachaolish on the south shore of Loch Creran. By 1881 she was living with her
                    grandson Donald MacPhee, ploughman, his wife Mary and two sons, at Linneveithe,
                    evidently a house just beyond Drumavuic on the south side of the River Creran. </p>
                <p>Mary Carmichael died of palsy in 1889 and her grandson Donald MacPhee is recorded
                    as witness on her death certificate.</p>
                <p>Alexander Carmichael recorded the Fenian lay Laoidh na Ceàrdaich from Mary
                    Carmichael, Drumavuic, on the 29 August 1883 [CW120/80], on the way back down
                    Glen Creran after his first interview with the foxhunter Donald MacColl, ‘Am
                    Brocair’, in Fasnacloich. The hurried way Carmichael dashed down the text
                    suggests that he was not entirely involved with the performance. Mary may also
                    have given Carmichael the items which followed: the song Am bun a’ chruidh cha
                    chaidil mi [or, better, cha chaithris mi: see, for example, John Mackenzie
                    (ed.), <span localType="mods-titleinfo">Sàr-Obair nam Bàrd Gaelach</span>
                    (Edinburgh, 1882), 367, with an associated local legend concerning a fairy
                    lover, as well as a tale about a changeling wife [CW120/82]. </p>
